  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which knee is best for replacement surgery?",
  "response": "Choosing the best type of knee replacement surgery depends on several factors, including the extent of knee damage, your overall health, activity level, and specific medical needs. Here are the main types of knee replacement procedures:\n\n1. **Total Knee Replacement (TKR):**\n   - **Description:** Replaces the entire knee joint, including the damaged bones, cartilage, and ligaments.\n   - **Best For:** Individuals with severe arthritis or extensive knee damage affecting multiple parts of the knee.\n\n2. **Partial Knee Replacement (PKR) or Unicompartmental Knee Replacement:**\n   - **Description:** Only the damaged compartment of the knee is replaced, leaving the healthy areas intact.\n   - **Best For:** Patients with arthritis confined to a single part of the knee, typically the inner or outer compartment.\n\n3. **Customized or Patient-Specific Knee Replacement:**\n   - **Description:** Utilizes advanced imaging and computer modeling to create implants tailored to the patient\u2019s unique knee anatomy.\n   - **Best For:** Those seeking a personalized fit and potentially improved alignment and function.\n\n4. **Minimally Invasive Knee Replacement:**\n   - **Description:** Involves smaller incisions and less disruption of surrounding tissues compared to traditional surgery.\n   - **Best For:** Individuals looking for shorter recovery times and reduced postoperative pain.\n\n5. **Robotic-Assisted Knee Replacement:**\n   - **Description:** Employs robotic technology to enhance precision in implant placement and alignment.\n   - **Best For:** Patients interested in the latest surgical technologies for potentially improved outcomes.\n\n**Factors to Consider When Choosing the Best Option:**\n\n- **Severity and Location of Damage:** Determines whether a partial or total replacement is more appropriate.\n- **Age and Activity Level:** Younger, more active individuals might benefit from certain types of implants designed for durability.\n- **Overall Health:** Influences the type of surgery and anesthesia used.\n- **Surgeon\u2019s Expertise:** The experience and specialization of your orthopedic surgeon can impact the choice of procedure.\n- **Recovery Time and Rehabilitation Needs:** Different procedures may have varying recovery trajectories.\n\n**Next Steps:**\n\nIt's essential to consult with an orthopedic surgeon who can evaluate your specific condition and recommend the most suitable type of knee replacement for you. They will consider all relevant factors, perform necessary diagnostic tests, and discuss the potential risks and benefits to help you make an informed decision.",
